The '''forest raven''' (''Corvus tasmanicus'', also commonly known as the '''Tasmanian raven''') is a [[passerine]] bird in the family [[Corvidae]] native to Tasmania and parts of southern [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], such as [[Wilsons Promontory]] and [[Portland, Victoria|Portland]]. Populations are also found in parts of [[New South Wales]], including [[Dorrigo, New South Wales|Dorrigo]] and [[Armidale, New South Wales|Armidale]]. Measuring {{convert|50|–|53|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length, it has all-black plumage, beak and legs. As with the other two species of raven in [[Australia]], its black feathers have grey bases. Adults have white [[iris (anatomy)|iris]]es; younger birds have dark brown and then hazel irises with an inner blue rim. New South Wales populations are recognised as a separate subspecies ''C. tasmanicus boreus'', but appear to be nested within the Tasmanian subspecies genetically.

The forest raven lives in a wide variety of habitats in Tasmania but is restricted to more closed forest on mainland Australia. Breeding takes place in spring and summer, occurring later in Tasmania than in New South Wales. The nest is a bowl-shaped structure of sticks sited high in a tree. An [[omnivore|omnivorous]] and opportunistic feeder, it eats a wide variety of plant and animal material, as well as food waste from urban areas and roadkill. It has been blamed for killing lambs and poultry and raiding orchards in Tasmania, and is unprotected under Tasmanian legislation. The forest raven is sedentary, with pairs generally bonding for life and establishing permanent territories.

==Taxonomy and naming==
[[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] described the "South-Seas raven" in 1781, with loose throat feathers and found in "the Friendly Isles" in the South Seas, but did not give a binomial name.<ref>{{cite book|last=Latham|first=John|title=A General Synopsis of Birds|publisher= Benj. White|location=London, United Kingdom|date=1781|volume=1|pages=369|url=http://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33727899}}</ref> Although "the Friendly Isles" refers to Tonga,<ref name="rowley 1970">{{cite journal|last=Rowley|first=Ian|date=1970|title=The Genus ''Corvus'' (Aves: Corvidae) in Australia|journal=CSIRO Wildlife Research|volume=15|issue=1|pages=27–71|doi=10.1071/CWR9700027}}</ref> the specimen resembles what is now known as the forest raven and was collected by ships' surgeon [[William Anderson (naturalist)|William Anderson]] on the [[third voyage of James Cook]] in January 1777. Tasked as the expedition's naturalist, Anderson collected many bird specimens but had died of [[tuberculosis]] in 1778 before the return home. Many collection localities were incorrect, and notes were lost or pieced together many years later.<ref name="Stresemann 1950">{{cite journal|last=Stresemann|first=Erwin|date=1950 |title=Birds collected during Capt. James Cook's last expedition (1776–1780)|journal=The Auk|volume=67|issue=1|pages=66–88|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v067n01/p0066-p0088.pdf}}</ref> German naturalist [[Johann Friedrich Gmelin]] gave the species the name ''Corvus australis'' in the 13th edition of ''Systema naturae'' in 1788.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gmelin|first=Johann Friedrich|title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae :secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis /Caroli a Linné|publisher=Impensis Georg. Emanuel. Beer|location=Leipzig, Germany|date=1788|pages=365|url=http://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2896965}}</ref>

Since Australia was settled by Europeans, all species of crows and ravens have been colloquially known as crows by the general population and are difficult to distinguish.<ref name="rowley 1970"/> In his 1865 ''[[Handbook to the Birds of Australia]]'', [[John Gould]] noted a single species of corvid in Australia, ''Corvus australis'', which he called the white-eyed crow. He used Gmelin's 1788 name, which took precedence by virtue of its age over Vigors and Horsfield's description.<ref name="gould 1865">{{cite book|last=Gould|first=John|title=Handbook to The birds of Australia|publisher=self|location=London, United Kingdom|date=1865|pages=475 |url=http://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/8460042}}</ref> In 1912 Scottish naturalist [[William Robert Ogilvie-Grant]] clarified the species as ''C. coronoides'' (raven, and incorporating [[little raven|little]] and [[Australian raven]]s) and ''C. cecilae'' ([[Torresian crow]]).<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ogilvie-Grant|first=William Robert|date=1912|title=The Crows of Australia|journal=Emu|volume=12|issue=1|pages=44–45|doi=10.1071/MU912044 }}</ref> Subsequently, French-American ornithologist [[Charles Vaurie]] acted as [[International Code of Zoological Nomenclature#Principle of the First Reviser|First Revisor]] under Article 24 of the [[International Code of Zoological Nomenclature]] (ICZN) Code and discarded ''C. australis'' as a junior homonym—in 1788, Gmelin had used the same binomial name to describe the [[black nunbird]]—to preserve the stability of the name.<ref name="Vaurie62">{{cite book|last=Vaurie|first=Charles|title=Check-list of Birds of the World|editor=Mayr, Ernst|publisher=Harvard University Press|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|date=1962|edition=XV|pages=261|url=http://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14485649}}</ref> This has been followed by later authors.<ref>{{cite book |title=Directory of Australian Birds: Passerines |first1=Richard |last1=Schodde |first2=I. J. |last2=Mason |year=1999 |publisher=CSIRO |location=Collingwood, Victoria |isbn=978-0-643-10293-4|page=609}}</ref><!-- cites previous two sentences -->

[[Gregory Mathews]] described the forest raven as a distinct subspecies—''Corvus marianae tasmanicus''—of the Australian raven in 1912,{{efn|1=Mathews used the binomial name ''Corvus marianae'' for the Australian raven}} its species name derived from Tasmania, the type locality.{{sfn|Higgins|2006|p=717}} Rowley raised the forest raven to species rank in 1970, noting there were no intermediate forms between it and the little raven (its closest relative) and that it was clearly larger with a much more massive bill. He described a second subspecies—''Corvus tasmanicus boreus''—the same year, observing that ''C. tasmanicus'' from Tasmania and southern Victoria has a very short tail compared with individuals from the northern New South Wales population.<ref name="rowley 1970"/><!-- cites previous two sentences --> Rowley gave the species name forest raven in 1970. The term "crow" is colloquially applied to any or all species of Australian corvid.<ref name="rowley 1970"/>

